{
  "texts": [
    "A crucial framework inspiring us on L1 transfer and crosslinguistic influence is the Differential Markedness Hypothesis proposed by Eckman (1977), which defined markedness as follows: a phenomenon A in some language is more marked than B if the presence of A in a language implies the presence of B but not vice versa.",
    "Eckman (1977) provides an example to illustrate the theory, demonstrating that certain languages, such as Arabic and Greek, allow passive sentences without explicitly stated agents (as shown in example 4a), but not with explicitly stated agents (as in example 4b).",
    "Conversely, languages such as English, French, and Japanese accommodate both types of passive sentences.",
    "However, there seems to be no languages where passive constructions with agents exist independently of those without agents.",
    "Thus, the existence of passive sentences with agents implies the existence of passive sentences without agents, but not vice versa."
  ]
}